<PageShell
  title="BUPA Global vs SafetyWing"
  description="Compare BUPA Global and SafetyWing Nomad for expat coverage. Premium health insurance vs budget travel medical—understand what you're actually comparing."
  headline="BUPA Global vs SafetyWing: Health Insurance vs Travel Medical"
  subheadline="These aren't competing products—they're different categories. Understanding that difference is the key to choosing right."
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/compare/bupa-vs-safetywing-hero-bg.png"
  heroImage="/images/pages/provider-card-generic.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get BUPA Global Quote"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/bupa-global"
>
  <h2 id="overview">Overview</h2>
  <p>
    BUPA Global and SafetyWing appear to compete in the same space—international coverage for people living or traveling abroad. But they're fundamentally different products solving different problems at vastly different price points.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>BUPA Global</strong> offers comprehensive international health insurance. They cover everything from annual checkups to chronic disease management to mental health treatment. Founded in 1947, BUPA (British United Provident Association) serves over 43 million customers in 190+ countries. They're one of the most recognized names in international health insurance, known for thorough coverage and exceptional mental health benefits.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>SafetyWing Nomad Insurance</strong> is travel medical insurance designed for digital nomads and remote workers. It covers emergencies and accidents—broken bones, sudden illness, unexpected hospitalizations—but not routine care, chronic conditions, or mental health. Founded in 2018 by Scandinavian entrepreneurs, SafetyWing has gained popularity among the digital nomad community for its low cost and subscription-based flexibility.
  </p>
  <p>
    Here's the critical distinction: <strong>SafetyWing is not health insurance.</strong> It's travel medical coverage. BUPA Global is actual health insurance. Comparing them directly is like comparing car insurance to an extended warranty—they serve different purposes.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-300 rounded-lg p-6 my-8">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Important: Product Category Warning</h3>
    <p class="text-neutral-700">
      Before comparing prices, understand what you're buying. SafetyWing Nomad is <strong>travel medical insurance</strong>, not health insurance. It doesn't cover:
    </p>
    <ul class="text-neutral-700 mt-2 space-y-1">
      <li>• Mental health treatment</li>
      <li>• Pre-existing conditions</li>
      <li>• Routine checkups or preventive care</li>
      <li>• Chronic condition management (diabetes, high blood pressure, etc.)</li>
      <li>• Planned surgeries or treatments</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="text-neutral-700 mt-3">
      If you need any of these, SafetyWing isn't an option regardless of price.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-purple-50 border border-purple-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">BUPA Global</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-600">
        <li><strong>Type:</strong> Comprehensive Health Insurance</li>
        <li><strong>Founded:</strong> 1947 (UK)</li>
        <li><strong>Customers:</strong> 43+ million worldwide</li>
        <li><strong>Strength:</strong> Mental health, comprehensive coverage</li>
        <li><strong>Price Range:</strong> $200-650+/month</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-teal-50 border border-teal-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">SafetyWing Nomad</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-600">
        <li><strong>Type:</strong> Travel Medical Insurance</li>
        <li><strong>Founded:</strong> 2018 (Norway)</li>
        <li><strong>Customers:</strong> Growing nomad community</li>
        <li><strong>Strength:</strong> Low cost, flexibility</li>
        <li><strong>Price Range:</strong> $42-120/month</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="quick-decision">Quick Decision Guide</h2>
  <p>
    This decision often makes itself once you understand what each product covers.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-gradient-to-r from-purple-50 to-teal-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-8">
    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">You NEED BUPA Global (or similar health insurance) if:</h3>
    <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-700 mb-6">
      <li>✓ You have any pre-existing conditions</li>
      <li>✓ You take regular medications</li>
      <li>✓ Mental health coverage matters to you</li>
      <li>✓ You want routine checkups covered</li>
      <li>✓ You might get pregnant or are planning to</li>
      <li>✓ You're over 40 or have emerging health concerns</li>
      <li>✓ You want comprehensive, worry-free coverage</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">SafetyWing MIGHT work if:</h3>
    <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-700 mb-6">
      <li>✓ You're young and genuinely healthy</li>
      <li>✓ You have no pre-existing conditions</li>
      <li>✓ You don't need mental health coverage</li>
      <li>✓ You can pay out-of-pocket for routine care</li>
      <li>✓ You only want emergency/accident coverage</li>
      <li>✓ Budget is your primary concern</li>
      <li>✓ You're comfortable with coverage gaps</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Quick Test:</h3>
    <p class="text-neutral-700">
      Ask yourself: "Would I be okay paying $200-500 out of pocket for a doctor visit, blood work, or prescriptions?" If yes, SafetyWing might work. If that sounds stressful or unaffordable, you need actual health insurance.
    </p>
    <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3 mt-6">
      <a href="/go/bupa-global" class="inline-block px-5 py-2.5 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-primary-700 transition-colors font-medium" style="color: white !important;">Get BUPA Global Quote</a>
      <a href="/go/safetywing" class="inline-block px-5 py-2.5 bg-neutral-700 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-neutral-800 transition-colors font-medium" style="color: white !important;">Get SafetyWing Quote</a>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="what-comparing">What You're Actually Comparing</h2>
  <p>
    Understanding the product category difference is essential before comparing features or prices.
  </p>

  <h3>BUPA Global: Comprehensive Health Insurance</h3>
  <p>
    Health insurance covers your ongoing health needs—not just emergencies. With BUPA Global you get:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Routine care:</strong> Annual physicals, blood work, screenings, vaccinations</li>
    <li><strong>Chronic condition management:</strong> Diabetes, hypertension, asthma—ongoing treatment and medications</li>
    <li><strong>Mental health:</strong> Therapy, psychiatry, inpatient mental health treatment (BUPA is known for exceptional mental health coverage)</li>
    <li><strong>Specialist care:</strong> Dermatologists, cardiologists, endocrinologists—whoever you need</li>
    <li><strong>Pre-existing conditions:</strong> Covered after a waiting period (typically 12-24 months)</li>
    <li><strong>Maternity:</strong> Full pregnancy and delivery coverage (add-on with waiting period)</li>
    <li><strong>Emergency care:</strong> Also covered, of course</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>SafetyWing Nomad: Travel Medical Insurance</h3>
  <p>
    Travel medical insurance covers unexpected emergencies while traveling—that's it. SafetyWing covers:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Emergencies:</strong> Accidents, sudden illness, unexpected hospitalization</li>
    <li><strong>Medical evacuation:</strong> Getting you to appropriate care (up to $100,000)</li>
    <li><strong>Emergency dental:</strong> Tooth pain, infections (limited)</li>
    <li><strong>Limited outpatient:</strong> Some coverage, but capped at $1,500</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    What SafetyWing explicitly does NOT cover:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Pre-existing conditions:</strong> Any condition you had before enrolling</li>
    <li><strong>Mental health:</strong> Therapy, psychiatry, mental health hospitalization</li>
    <li><strong>Routine care:</strong> Checkups, physicals, screenings</li>
    <li><strong>Ongoing treatment:</strong> Cancer treatment, dialysis, chronic disease management</li>
    <li><strong>Planned procedures:</strong> Anything you know you need before enrolling</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="bg-neutral-100 border border-neutral-300 rounded-lg p-6 my-8">
    <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">The Analogy</h4>
    <p class="text-neutral-700">
      Think of it like car coverage. <strong>BUPA Global</strong> is like having car insurance PLUS a maintenance plan—oil changes, brake pads, tune-ups, plus collision and liability coverage.
    </p>
    <p class="text-neutral-700 mt-2">
      <strong>SafetyWing</strong> is like having collision-only coverage—if you crash, you're covered. But oil changes, brake pads, and that weird engine noise? All on you.
    </p>
    <p class="text-neutral-700 mt-2">
      Both have their place, but they solve different problems.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="coverage-comparison">Coverage Comparison</h2>
  <p>
    Here's a detailed breakdown of what each product actually covers.
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={coverageColumns} rows={coverageRows} />
  </div>

  <h3>Key Coverage Gaps in SafetyWing</h3>
  <p>
    The most significant gaps in SafetyWing coverage that catch people off guard:
  </p>

  <p><strong>1. Outpatient Cap ($1,500)</strong></p>
  <p>
    SafetyWing limits outpatient coverage to $1,500 per "certificate period" (4 weeks). One specialist visit with blood work could eat half that. A few doctor visits and you've exhausted it.
  </p>

  <p><strong>2. No Mental Health</strong></p>
  <p>
    Zero mental health coverage. No therapy, no psychiatry, no mental health medications. If you're struggling abroad and need help, SafetyWing won't cover it.
  </p>

  <p><strong>3. No Pre-Existing Conditions</strong></p>
  <p>
    If you have any condition that existed before enrollment—high blood pressure, diabetes, anxiety, anything—it's not covered. Flare-ups of existing conditions? Not covered.
  </p>

  <p><strong>4. No Routine Care</strong></p>
  <p>
    Annual checkups, cancer screenings, vaccinations, preventive care—all out of pocket. SafetyWing only kicks in when something unexpected goes wrong.
  </p>

  <p><strong>5. Prescription Limits</strong></p>
  <p>
    Prescriptions are capped at $150 per certificate period. If you need any regular medication, you're paying out of pocket.
  </p>

  <h2 id="plan-tiers">Plan Options</h2>
  <p>
    The plan structures are fundamentally different—BUPA offers comprehensive tiers, SafetyWing has one product.
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={planColumns} rows={planRows} />
  </div>

  <h3>BUPA Global Plan Tiers</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Essentials:</strong> Core coverage with $2M maximum. Hospital and outpatient basics</li>
    <li><strong>Comprehensive:</strong> Mid-tier with enhanced benefits. More specialist coverage and higher limits</li>
    <li><strong>Premier:</strong> Top-tier with unlimited maximum. Extensive wellness benefits, enhanced mental health, and no practical coverage limits</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    All tiers include BUPA's exceptional mental health coverage and access to their global hospital network.
  </p>

  <h3>SafetyWing Nomad</h3>
  <p>
    SafetyWing offers one plan—Nomad Insurance. There's no tier selection. What you see is what you get:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>$250,000 maximum coverage</li>
    <li>$250 deductible (fixed)</li>
    <li>$1,500 outpatient limit per 4-week period</li>
    <li>$100,000 medical evacuation</li>
    <li>15 days of US/home country coverage per 90 days</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The simplicity is part of the appeal—one plan, one price, take it or leave it.
  </p>

  <h2 id="pricing">Pricing Comparison</h2>
  <p>
    Here's where SafetyWing's appeal becomes clear—and where the danger lies. The price difference is dramatic: 75-85% lower. But you're getting a fundamentally different (and much more limited) product.
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={pricingColumns} rows={pricingRows} />
  </div>

  <p><em>*BUPA Global prices are for mid-tier plans (Comprehensive) with moderate deductibles. Actual premiums vary based on age, health history, area of coverage, and selected benefits. SafetyWing prices are standard rates from their website.</em></p>

  <h3>Why the Huge Price Difference?</h3>
  <p>
    The 75-85% price gap reflects what's actually covered:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>BUPA covers everything:</strong> Routine care, chronic conditions, mental health, specialist visits, prescriptions—all the expensive stuff</li>
    <li><strong>SafetyWing covers emergencies only:</strong> They're betting most healthy young nomads won't have emergencies</li>
    <li><strong>BUPA has high limits:</strong> $2M minimum, unlimited on Premier</li>
    <li><strong>SafetyWing caps at $250,000:</strong> Adequate for most emergencies, but not for major illness</li>
    <li><strong>BUPA's claims are higher:</strong> Routine care means frequent claims; SafetyWing rarely pays out</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>The Hidden Cost of SafetyWing</h3>
  <p>
    SafetyWing's low price assumes you'll pay out-of-pocket for everything except emergencies. Calculate what you'd spend on:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Quarterly doctor visits: $150-400 each</li>
    <li>Annual blood work: $100-300</li>
    <li>Monthly prescriptions: $50-500+</li>
    <li>Dental cleanings: $75-200 each</li>
    <li>Therapy sessions: $100-250 each</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If you're truly healthy and never use these services, SafetyWing saves money. If you use even modest healthcare, the savings evaporate.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-8">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Calculate Your True Cost</h3>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-4">Factor in what you'll pay out-of-pocket with SafetyWing vs what BUPA covers.</p>
    <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3">
      <a href="/go/bupa-global" class="inline-block px-5 py-2.5 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-primary-700 transition-colors font-medium" style="color: white !important;">Get BUPA Global Quote</a>
      <a href="/go/safetywing" class="inline-block px-5 py-2.5 bg-neutral-700 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-neutral-800 transition-colors font-medium" style="color: white !important;">Get SafetyWing Quote</a>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="network-and-claims">Network and Claims</h2>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={networkColumns} rows={networkRows} />
  </div>

  <h3>BUPA Global Network</h3>
  <p>
    BUPA maintains relationships with hospitals worldwide. In major cities, you can often receive care without paying upfront—BUPA bills the hospital directly. Their member services team coordinates care for complex cases, arranges second opinions, and navigates local healthcare systems on your behalf.
  </p>

  <h3>SafetyWing "Network"</h3>
  <p>
    SafetyWing doesn't have a traditional network. You pay for care, then submit claims for reimbursement. In some cases, they can arrange direct billing with hospitals, but don't count on it. The claims process is simple (limited coverage means simple claims) but you'll typically pay upfront.
  </p>

  <h3>Claims Process Comparison</h3>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={claimsColumns} rows={claimsRows} />
  </div>

  <h2 id="mental-health">Mental Health Coverage</h2>
  <p>
    This deserves special attention because it's where these products differ most dramatically—and where SafetyWing's gaps can cause real harm.
  </p>

  <h3>BUPA Global: Industry-Leading Mental Health</h3>
  <p>
    BUPA Global is known for exceptional mental health coverage:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Full parity:</strong> Mental health treated same as physical health</li>
    <li><strong>Outpatient therapy:</strong> Sessions with psychologists and counselors</li>
    <li><strong>Psychiatry:</strong> Medication management and psychiatric care</li>
    <li><strong>Inpatient treatment:</strong> Mental health hospitalization when needed</li>
    <li><strong>No separate limits:</strong> Uses same annual maximum as physical health</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If you're managing anxiety, depression, or any mental health condition—or want the option to address issues that arise—BUPA provides genuine support.
  </p>

  <h3>SafetyWing: Zero Mental Health Coverage</h3>
  <p>
    SafetyWing explicitly excludes all mental health:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>No therapy coverage</li>
    <li>No psychiatry</li>
    <li>No mental health medications</li>
    <li>No mental health hospitalization</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If you experience a mental health crisis abroad with SafetyWing, you're on your own financially. This is a serious gap for anyone who might need mental health support.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-red-50 border border-red-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-8">
    <h4 class="font-semibold text-red-800 mb-2">Mental Health Warning</h4>
    <p class="text-red-700">
      Living abroad can be isolating. Culture shock, loneliness, and adjustment issues are common. If there's any chance you might need mental health support, SafetyWing won't help. This isn't theoretical—many expats need mental health care during their time abroad.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="real-scenarios">Real-World Scenarios</h2>

  <div class="space-y-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Healthy 26-Year-Old Digital Nomad</h4>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">
        Maya works remotely, travels through Southeast Asia, has no health conditions, and hasn't seen a doctor in three years. She's comfortable paying cash for occasional clinic visits.
      </p>
      <p class="text-primary-700 font-medium">→ SafetyWing fits her profile. She needs emergency coverage, not comprehensive health insurance. The $45/month price is appropriate for her low-risk situation.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">35-Year-Old Remote Worker with Anxiety</h4>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">
        James manages anxiety with weekly therapy and daily medication. He's moving abroad to work remotely and wants to continue his treatment.
      </p>
      <p class="text-primary-700 font-medium">→ BUPA Global is essential. SafetyWing wouldn't cover his therapy or medications—he'd pay $500-800/month out of pocket on top of SafetyWing's premium. BUPA's comprehensive coverage actually costs less than SafetyWing + out-of-pocket care.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">45-Year-Old with Managed Hypertension</h4>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">
        Linda takes blood pressure medication daily and needs quarterly checkups. Her condition is well-controlled but requires ongoing management.
